// TEST: exec_go_class_trait_method_casing
// EXPECT: output "btn:click!;page:[click!]"
// EXPECT: targets go
//
// Go class/trait method-name casing + no self-recursive forwarder. A class has
// an *inherent* method (`render`) whose name a `trait` the class implements also
// declares. Go interface methods are always exported (PascalCase), so the
// inherent method must be declared `Render` too (it is the real implementation
// that satisfies the interface), and every dispatch site — `self.render()`,
// `w.render()`, `card.render()` — must agree on `Render`.
//
// Two defects this guards:
//   1. Casing: before the fix the inherent `render` emitted lowercase `render`
//      while dispatch / `impl Component` expected `Render`
//      (`page.Render undefined (has method render)`).
//   2. Recursion: under the single-method-namespace rule (DQ27, spec §6.7) a
//      type has one method namespace, so `render` is defined exactly *once* —
//      here, as the inherent `Button.render` — and `impl Component for Button`
//      is empty. The inherent exported `Render` satisfies the interface
//      directly. (The previous form declared `render` in both blocks with a
//      `self.render()` forwarder, which is now an E4012 coherence error and
//      had emitted `func (Button) Render() { return self.Render() }` —
//      infinite recursion.)
//
// `Widget.render` is inherent with NO `impl Component for Widget`, proving an
// inherent method is exported when a trait merely *declares* the name. js/ts/
// python/rust dispatch by source name; this proves Go's casing now agrees.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (Go entry-point rationale).
module main

trait Component {
  fn render(self) -> String
}

class Button {
  label: String
}

impl Button {
  fn render(self) -> String {
    "${self.label}!"
  }
}

// Button is a Component via its inherent `render` (one method namespace, §6.7).
impl Component for Button {}

record Widget {
  inner: String
}

impl Widget {
  fn render(self) -> String {
    "[${self.inner}]"
  }
}

fn render_one(c: Button) -> String {
  c.render()
}

fn main() -> Void {
  let b = Button { label: "click" }
  let w = Widget { inner: render_one(b) }
  println("btn:${b.render()};page:${w.render()}")
}
